    "urn:li:comment:(activity:7472372860817178624,7475514742158184448)": {
      "comment_urn": "urn:li:comment:(activity:7472372860817178624,7475514742158184448)",
      "commented_at": "2026-06-24T11:46:42Z",
      "verb": "commented",
      "text": "Thank you for a nice read, it caught my attention and made me think.\nThe whole idea is built on catching the wrong turn early. But those two hours after the agent veers off aren't my two hours, they're the agent's. It costs some tokens, sure, yet the time isn't mine to protect, so the stage where I catch the mistake matters far less than it feels like. Also in the first two minutes I usually can't even tell whether the run is going wrong or going somewhere I didn't expect. \n\nmaybe half the times I jump in to \"fix\" the agent, I later find it was right and I was wrong. It took that path because the API call I assumed existed doesn't, and it already knew that. I only learn this by asking it why it went there, not by hitting Escape at minute two. So for me the truth comes out of talking to the run, not steering it.\n\nThat's why I'd put the effort somewhere else: self-validation before the PR. Let the agent check its own work in the gap between the wrong turn and the diff, so it can correct itself.",
      "comment_author_name": "Peter Ovchynnikov",
      "comment_author_url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/ovchyn",
      "post_urn": "urn:li:activity:7475514769328955392",
      "post_url": "https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7475514769328955392/",
      "post_author_name": "Greg Ceccarelli",
      "post_author_url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/gregceccarelli",
      "permalink": "https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7475514769328955392/?commentUrn=urn%3Ali%3Acomment%3A%28activity%3A7472372860817178624%2C7475514742158184448%29",
      "weeks": {
        "2026-06-29": {
          "snapshot_at": "2026-06-29T06:36:48Z",
          "reactions": 0,
          "replies_count": 0,
          "impressions": 18
        },
        "2026-07-13": {
          "snapshot_at": "2026-07-16T18:16:24Z",
          "reactions": 0,
          "replies_count": 0,
          "impressions": 22
        }
